[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C6, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against the spade slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Board four, and the stakes rise: 6\S, twelve tricks. Count eleven, and stare at the twelfth: dummy's \DA-Q-9-3 over your J-6-5, missing the king. Every beginner in the room reaches for the finesse. You have spent two shelves learning why the expert reaches for something else first. The trumps are solid and long. Before you commit a single diamond, ask what the rest of the hand could tell you first.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The finesse was there; the squeeze made it beneath you. That is the deepest lesson of the shelf: pressure first, and the guesses answer themselves — sometimes, as here, by the king simply falling out of a broken hand. One slam in the bag; two boards remain.}
