{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \D3, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against the heart game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] The final board, and the exam saves its favorite question for last: WHEN do you take your losses? You are in 4\H with trump honors missing and a diamond coming at you into dummy's K-T. The reflex is to grab the king. Count first: the defense has tricks that cannot be denied — but every one of them can be TIMED. Decide, before you play a card from dummy, which trick of this hand you are going to lose on purpose.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The exam's last answer was the shelf's first lesson: the trick you surrender at trick one buys the endgame — the duck kept control, the run did the squeezing, and a four took a trick. Across these six boards you threw kings to wolves, handed defenders their own winners, and never once took a blind fifty-fifty. That is what these two shelves were for: the finesse is a fine tool — and the best players spend the whole hand arranging never to need it. Exam complete; beautifully played.}
[Note "1:Inviting Jump Shifts"]
